Decorators that take arguments — the three-level shape.

When you want at-retry of times equals three instead of plain at-retry, you need one extra level. The signature changes from function in, function out to args in, decorator out, which itself is function in, function out.

Picture def retry taking times. Inner def decorator takes func. Inside that, at-wraps of func, def wrapper takes star-args double-star-kwargs and does the retry logic. Return wrapper. Return decorator.

The shape is awkward the first time. The trick to reading it — count the levels from the outside in. Each def is one rung. And the at-retry of times equals three call site evaluates from the outside in too.

In code, picture from functools import wraps. Def retry of times. Inner def decorator of func. Inner def wrapper with star-args. Body loops up to times, tries func, catches any exception, prints attempt failed. If all attempts fail, raises the last error. Then a flaky function — at-retry of times equals three on def flaky, which fails seventy percent of the time. Calling flaky retries until it succeeds.
